@startuml 10-private-video-playback

!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FEFEFE
title Flow 10: Private Video Playback (Seal Decryption)

actor "End User" as User
participant "Hosted Player Page\n(Browser)" as Player
participant "Seal SDK\n(Client)" as SealSDK
participant "Seal\nKey Servers" as KeyServer
participant "Platform\nBackend" as Backend
database "Sui\nBlockchain" as Sui
database "Walrus\nStorage" as Walrus

note over Player
  Private video playback requires the hosted player page (/watch/{video_id}).
  Segments are AES-encrypted — a raw .m3u8 URL will not work in a generic player.
  Decryption happens inside a custom hls.js loader before bytes reach the <video> element.
end note

== User Initiates Playback ==

User -> Player: Click play on private video

Player -> Backend: GET /v/{video_id}/info
Backend -> Backend: Check: is_private = true
Backend --> Player: {\n  is_private: true,\n  encrypted_key: "...",\n  package_id: "0x..."\n}

== Wallet Authentication (One-time) ==

Player -> Player: Detect: private video\nrequires wallet

Player -> User: "Sign to access this video"\n(wallet popup)

User -> Player: Signs message with wallet

Player -> SealSDK: SessionKey.create(\n  address: user_wallet,\n  packageId: access_policy_pkg,\n  ttlMin: 10\n)

SealSDK --> Player: session_key (valid 10 min)

== Fetch Decryption Key from Seal ==

Player -> SealSDK: client.decrypt(\n  data: encrypted_aes_key,\n  sessionKey: session_key,\n  txBytes: seal_approve_tx\n)

SealSDK -> KeyServer: Request derived key\nfor identity [pkg][video_id]

KeyServer -> Sui: Dry-run seal_approve(\n  id: video_id,\n  sender: user_wallet\n)

Sui -> Sui: Check whitelist:\nIs user_wallet in\nvideo.whitelist?

alt User NOT in whitelist
    Sui --> KeyServer: ABORT: ENoAccess
    KeyServer --> SealSDK: Access denied
    SealSDK --> Player: Error: Not authorized
    Player --> User: "You don't have\naccess to this video"
else User IS in whitelist
    Sui --> KeyServer: OK (no abort)
    KeyServer -> KeyServer: Derive secret key\nfor identity
    KeyServer --> SealSDK: derived_key
end

== Client-Side Key Decryption ==

SealSDK -> SealSDK: Decrypt AES key locally\nusing derived_key

SealSDK --> Player: aes_key (32 bytes)

Player -> Player: Store aes_key in memory\nInitialize custom hls.js loader\nwith aes_key

note right of Player
  AES key is now in browser memory.
  Backend NEVER sees this key.
  The custom hls.js loader will use it
  to decrypt every manifest and segment
  response before passing bytes to the
  <video> element. No manual decryption
  step is needed during playback.
end note

== Stream & Decrypt Video ==

Player -> Backend: GET /v/{video_id}/stream.m3u8\n(via custom hls.js loader)
Backend -> Walrus: Read encrypted manifest
Walrus --> Backend: encrypted_manifest
Backend --> Player: encrypted_manifest

Player -> Player: custom loader:\nAES.decrypt(manifest, aes_key)\nPass decrypted manifest to hls.js

loop For each HLS segment
    Player -> Backend: GET /v/{video_id}/seg_{n}.ts\n(via custom hls.js loader)
    Backend -> Walrus: Read encrypted segment
    Walrus --> Backend: encrypted_segment
    Backend --> Player: encrypted_segment

    Player -> Player: custom loader:\nAES.decrypt(segment, aes_key)\nFeed decrypted bytes to MSE\nPlay segment
end

note right of Player
  Each segment decryption is
  instant (AES is fast).
  No more Seal requests needed
  for the duration of the session.
end note

@enduml
